definitions: not having necessary backing, evidence, or foundation to be considered valid or reliable
examples: Her claims were completely unsupported by any evidence
The unsupported structure finally collapsed under its own weight

definitions: not certain or confident about something; experiencing doubt or hesitation
examples: She felt unsure about her decision to change careers
The students looked unsure when asked the difficult question

definitions: better than all others in quality, degree, or achievement; having no equal
examples: Her unsurpassed talent made her the obvious choice for lead
The restaurant's unsurpassed service kept customers returning year after year

definitions: causing no surprise because it was expected or predictable given the circumstances
examples: It was unsurprising that traffic was heavy during rush hour
The team's victory was unsurprising given their excellent record

definitions: not aware of the presence of danger or deceit; trusting and unaware
examples: The unsuspecting tourists walked right into the expensive trap
The prank was played on unsuspecting coworkers during lunch

definitions: not feeling, showing, or expressing sympathy, compassion, or understanding toward others
examples: The unsympathetic manager ignored his employee's personal crisis
Her unsympathetic response hurt more than the rejection itself

definitions: not domesticated or brought under control; remaining in a wild natural state
examples: The untamed wilderness stretched for miles beyond the camp
Her untamed spirit refused to conform to society's expectations

definitions: not yet used, exploited, or taken advantage of; having unused potential
examples: The region has vast untapped natural resources waiting for discovery
She realized her untapped potential after taking the art class

definitions: not able to be maintained, defended, or justified; impossible to sustain
examples: His position became untenable after the scandal broke
The untenable working conditions led to mass resignations

definitions: not yet tried, proven, or subjected to testing or examination
examples: The untested theory needed more research before acceptance
They were reluctant to hire untested candidates for critical roles

definitions: too unlikely, undesirable, or shocking to be considered as a possibility
examples: Twenty years ago, smartphones would have been unthinkable
It was unthinkable that such a tragedy could happen here

definitions: not neat or orderly in appearance; messy, disheveled, or disorganized
examples: His untidy desk made it hard to find important documents
The children left the playroom in an untidy state

definitions: not fastened, bound, or secured with string, rope, or similar material
examples: Her untied shoelaces posed a tripping hazard
The untied boat drifted away from the dock overnight

definitions: happening or done at an unsuitable, inappropriate, or inconvenient time
examples: His untimely interruption ruined the surprise announcement
The untimely rain forced them to cancel the outdoor wedding

definitions: continuing to work or make effort without showing signs of fatigue
examples: Her untiring efforts finally paid off with a promotion
The untiring volunteers worked through the night helping victims

definitions: having no title, name, or identifying heading; lacking formal designation
examples: The untitled painting was simply labeled with a number
She submitted an untitled manuscript to the publisher

definitions: too much or too many to be counted or measured
not told, revealed, or narrated; kept secret
examples: The disaster caused untold suffering to thousands of families
The company made untold millions from the new product
Her untold story remained a mystery for decades
The untold secrets of the organization finally came to light

definitions: unable to be affected, harmed, or defeated by outside forces
not to be touched, handled, or interfered with; forbidden
examples: The champion seemed untouchable after winning ten straight matches
His wealth made him feel untouchable by the law
The sacred artifacts were untouchable except by priests
In some cultures, certain people were considered untouchable

definitions: not affected, altered, or damaged in any way; remaining in original condition
examples: The ancient ruins remained untouched for thousands of years
Her dinner sat untouched while she dealt with the emergency

definitions: not having been trained, instructed, or educated for a particular skill or job
examples: The untrained workers made many costly mistakes
To the untrained eye, the paintings looked almost identical

definitions: not given medical care or treatment for a condition or illness
not processed, refined, or subjected to chemical or physical treatment
examples: The untreated infection spread rapidly through his system
Untreated depression can have serious long-term consequences
The untreated wood will weather naturally over time
They preferred untreated water straight from the mountain spring

definitions: not in accordance with fact or reality; false, incorrect, or inaccurate
examples: The rumors about her resignation were completely untrue
He knew his alibi was untrue but stuck to it

meanings: not able to be relied upon
definitions: not able to be relied upon as honest, truthful, or dependable in character or behavior
examples: The untrustworthy employee was caught stealing office supplies
That news source has proven untrustworthy many times before

definitions: not fit, suitable, or in proper condition for use or service
examples: The water was unusable due to contamination
The old software became unusable after the system update

definitions: not put to use or service; remaining idle or in original condition
examples: The unused gym membership was a waste of money
They found unused supplies in the storage room

definitions: not having received vaccines or immunizations against specific diseases
examples: Unvaccinated children were not allowed to attend school
The unvaccinated population remained vulnerable to the outbreak

definitions: revealed or presented to view after being hidden or covered
examples: The unveiled statue drew gasps from the impressed crowd
The company's unveiled plans showed ambitious growth targets

definitions: not confirmed, substantiated, or proven to be true or accurate
examples: The news outlet retracted the unverified report
Unverified claims spread quickly on social media

definitions: not desired, wished for, or welcome; rejected or surplus to requirements
examples: The unwanted furniture was donated to charity
She felt like an unwanted guest at the party

definitions: not justified, authorized, or deserved given the circumstances; lacking adequate grounds
examples: His unwarranted criticism hurt team morale
The police search was deemed unwarranted by the judge

definitions: steady and resolute; not wavering, faltering, or changing in determination or loyalty
examples: Her unwavering support helped him through difficult times
The team showed unwavering commitment to their goal

definitions: not married or joined in matrimony; single
examples: The unwed mother faced many challenges raising her child
He remained unwed well into his forties

definitions: not gladly received or accepted; causing displeasure or regarded as intrusive
examples: The unwelcome news dampened everyone's spirits
Rain was an unwelcome addition to their camping trip

definitions: not in good health; sick, ill, or indisposed
examples: She felt unwell and decided to leave work early
The unwell passengers were taken to the ship's medical center

definitions: difficult to carry, move, or handle because of size, shape, weight, or complexity
examples: The unwieldy package barely fit through the doorway
The committee's unwieldy structure made decisions nearly impossible

definitions: not wanting to do something; reluctant or refusing to act
examples: He was unwilling to compromise on the important issues
The unwilling participant had to be persuaded to join

definitions: showing poor judgment or lack of wisdom; foolish or imprudent
examples: It was unwise to invest all their savings in one stock
Her unwise comments offended many people

definitions: not aware of the full facts; done without knowing or intending
examples: She was an unwitting accomplice to the crime
His unwitting mistake cost the company thousands

definitions: not capable of being put into practice or made to work successfully
examples: The proposal was rejected as completely unworkable
Their unworkable schedule left no time for breaks

definitions: not deserving respect, attention, or effort; lacking merit or value
examples: He felt unworthy of her love and devotion
The movie was unworthy of its prestigious award

definitions: not written down or formally recorded but existing through custom or understanding
examples: They followed the unwritten rules of office etiquette
Their unwritten agreement had worked well for years

definitions: not giving way to pressure or persuasion; inflexible and determined
examples: Her unyielding stance on the issue frustrated negotiators
The unyielding rock face challenged even expert climbers

definitions: cheerful, optimistic, and positive in mood, manner, or outlook
examples: His upbeat attitude lifted everyone's spirits
The upbeat music got the party started

definitions: turned upside down or on its end; completely changed or disrupted
examples: The upended table blocked the restaurant entrance
Their lives were upended by the sudden job loss

definitions: frank, honest, and direct in manner or speech
paid or charged at the beginning before goods or services
examples: I appreciate your upfront communication about the problems
She was upfront about her lack of experience
The upfront costs were higher than expected
They required upfront payment before starting work

definitions: sloping upward; going up an incline or slope
requiring great effort or presenting constant difficulties
examples: The uphill path left them breathless
We faced an uphill climb to the summit
It was an uphill battle to change company policy
Getting approval seemed like an uphill struggle

definitions: relating to or situated on high or hilly land above the lowlands
examples: The upland regions received snow while valleys stayed dry
Upland farmers faced different challenges than those below

definitions: raised up to a higher position or level physically
feeling encouraged, inspired, or emotionally elevated in spirit
examples: The uplifted platform provided a better view
Geological forces created the uplifted mountain range
She felt uplifted after the inspiring speech
The uplifted crowd sang together in celebration

definitions: relatively expensive and designed to appeal to affluent consumers seeking quality
examples: The upmarket restaurant required formal dress
They moved to a more upmarket neighborhood

definitions: written or printed in capital letters rather than small letters
examples: Please write your name in uppercase letters
The uppercase text made the warning stand out
